        <p>Rather than linking to specific articles that go stale, this is a list of sources worth following — sites that consistently produce content relevant to single fathers.</p>

        <h2>Single dad and fatherhood sites</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.dadsdivorce.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DadsDivorce.com</a></strong><br>
            Forums, articles, and legal information specifically for fathers going through or recovering from divorce. The community boards are active and useful — real dads in similar situations.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.fatherly.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fatherly.com</a></strong><br>
            General fatherhood publication with a wide range of content — parenting, relationships, health, culture. Not single-dad specific but consistently relevant and well-written. Good for the "stuff I didn't know I needed to know" read.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.goodmenproject.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Good Men Project</a></strong><br>
            Broad publication on men's experiences including fatherhood, divorce, mental health, and relationships. Wide range of perspectives and voices. Hit or miss on quality but worth dipping into.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/SingleDads/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">r/SingleDads on Reddit</a></strong><br>
            Not a publication, but one of the most active communities for single fathers online. Good for real-world questions, venting, and hearing how other dads handled specific situations. Use the search before posting — most questions have been asked before.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Parenting research and practical guidance</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.zerotothree.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Zero to Three</a></strong><br>
            Research-backed resources for parents of children ages 0–3. If you have a baby or toddler, this is the best source for understanding what's actually going on developmentally and how to respond.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.verywellfamily.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Verywell Family</a></strong><br>
            Evidence-based parenting content across all ages. Better sourced than most parenting sites. Good for looking up specific topics — sleep, discipline, developmental milestones, school issues.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/parenting" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Psychology Today — Parenting</a></strong><br>
            Articles by psychologists and researchers on child development, co-parenting, and family dynamics. Useful when you want the clinical perspective rather than anecdotal advice.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Legal information</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/family-law" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Nolo — Family Law</a></strong><br>
            Plain-language legal explanations on custody, child support, divorce, and modification. Written by lawyers but accessible to non-lawyers. Good for understanding the framework before talking to an attorney.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.lawhelp.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LawHelp.org</a></strong><br>
            State-specific legal aid information and self-help resources for family court. More practical than Nolo — closer to actual forms and process for your specific state.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Mental health and personal development</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.nami.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">NAMI (National Alliance on Mental Illness)</a></strong><br>
            Reliable information on mental health conditions, treatment options, and finding help. Not parenting-specific, but the most credible source for mental health information when you need to understand something.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong><a href="https://www.1in6.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1in6.org</a></strong><br>
            Support and resources for men who have experienced trauma, including sexual abuse. Mentioned because it's underutilized — more men need it than know it exists.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>A note on social media parenting content:</strong> most of it is optimized for engagement, not accuracy. Parenting influencers, especially on Instagram and TikTok, tend to oversimplify, overgeneralize, and occasionally spread genuinely bad advice. Use the sources above for anything you actually want to act on.</p>
        </div>
